WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.200 --> 00:00:02.170
<v Instructor>So, let's talk about Consolidated Billing</v>

2
00:00:02.170 --> 00:00:04.120
for AWS Organization.

3
00:00:04.120 --> 00:00:05.330
So, when you enable this setting,

4
00:00:05.330 --> 00:00:06.820
this provides you two things.

5
00:00:06.820 --> 00:00:08.890
Number one, and I'll describe it in a second.

6
00:00:08.890 --> 00:00:10.440
It gives you the combined usage,

7
00:00:10.440 --> 00:00:12.530
that means that you can combine all the usage

8
00:00:12.530 --> 00:00:14.940
of all accounts together to do two things.

9
00:00:14.940 --> 00:00:18.080
Number one, you're going to share the volume pricing.

10
00:00:18.080 --> 00:00:19.760
For example, in Amazon history,

11
00:00:19.760 --> 00:00:22.450
if you go over maybe five terabytes of data,

12
00:00:22.450 --> 00:00:24.540
then the next service is going to be cheaper.

13
00:00:24.540 --> 00:00:26.080
Well, obviously if you combine

14
00:00:26.080 --> 00:00:27.090
all your accounts together,

15
00:00:27.090 --> 00:00:29.690
if every account is using one terabyte of data

16
00:00:29.690 --> 00:00:30.950
and you have six accounts,

17
00:00:30.950 --> 00:00:33.250
then altogether they will be benefiting

18
00:00:33.250 --> 00:00:34.330
from the discount pricing.

19
00:00:34.330 --> 00:00:36.330
So, the combined usage is very important,

20
00:00:36.330 --> 00:00:37.580
and also,

21
00:00:37.580 --> 00:00:39.240
there are some Reserved Instances

22
00:00:39.240 --> 00:00:41.590
or Savings Plan discounts on one account.

23
00:00:41.590 --> 00:00:43.140
They can be shared across all accounts

24
00:00:43.140 --> 00:00:45.220
again to maximize the discounts

25
00:00:45.220 --> 00:00:46.180
and the savings,

26
00:00:46.180 --> 00:00:47.800
and I will show you how in a second.

27
00:00:47.800 --> 00:00:49.820
The other advantage that it gives you,

28
00:00:49.820 --> 00:00:50.653
One Bill.

29
00:00:50.653 --> 00:00:52.610
So, get one bill for all the accounts

30
00:00:52.610 --> 00:00:53.630
in the organization,

31
00:00:53.630 --> 00:00:54.900
which really can help

32
00:00:54.900 --> 00:00:56.690
your accounting departments

33
00:00:56.690 --> 00:00:58.620
and allow you not to be restricted

34
00:00:58.620 --> 00:01:01.400
in how many accounts you can create for AWS.

35
00:01:01.400 --> 00:01:03.170
So, let's take an example of

36
00:01:03.170 --> 00:01:04.910
Reserved Instance Sharing.

37
00:01:04.910 --> 00:01:06.757
So we have an organization with two accounts

38
00:01:06.757 --> 00:01:08.200
and in the first one, account A,

39
00:01:08.200 --> 00:01:10.350
there is no Reserved Instances,

40
00:01:10.350 --> 00:01:11.210
and account B,

41
00:01:11.210 --> 00:01:13.600
there are five reserved EC2 instances.

42
00:01:13.600 --> 00:01:15.410
Now, let's assume that we are within one AZ

43
00:01:15.410 --> 00:01:18.300
because Reserve Instances are at the AZ level

44
00:01:18.300 --> 00:01:20.570
and we have nine EC2 instances.

45
00:01:20.570 --> 00:01:21.403
As you can see,

46
00:01:21.403 --> 00:01:23.170
three are launched in account B,

47
00:01:23.170 --> 00:01:25.550
and six are launched in account A.

48
00:01:25.550 --> 00:01:27.360
Now, what is going to happen?

49
00:01:27.360 --> 00:01:28.193
Well,

50
00:01:28.193 --> 00:01:31.630
if we have five EC2 Reserved Instances on account B,

51
00:01:31.630 --> 00:01:33.610
then the three EC2 instances

52
00:01:33.610 --> 00:01:34.890
obviously are going to be reserved,

53
00:01:34.890 --> 00:01:37.910
but because we have enabled Reserved Instances sharing,

54
00:01:37.910 --> 00:01:40.490
then two instances in account A

55
00:01:40.490 --> 00:01:43.200
will also benefit from Reserved Instances pricing

56
00:01:43.200 --> 00:01:45.270
and therefore rebuking cost savings.

57
00:01:45.270 --> 00:01:46.650
So, at the end of the day,

58
00:01:46.650 --> 00:01:48.140
we have five Reserved Instances

59
00:01:48.140 --> 00:01:50.880
and four not Reserved Instances in this use case

60
00:01:50.880 --> 00:01:52.930
even though Susan in account B

61
00:01:52.930 --> 00:01:54.990
only launched three EC2 instances

62
00:01:54.990 --> 00:01:56.950
out of the five that were reserved.

63
00:01:56.950 --> 00:01:57.783
Okay?

64
00:01:57.783 --> 00:01:59.020
So, you really need to understand this

65
00:01:59.020 --> 00:02:02.660
because the exam will test you on the shared volume pricing,

66
00:02:02.660 --> 00:02:04.030
so shared volume discounts

67
00:02:04.030 --> 00:02:06.960
and how to share and what it means

68
00:02:06.960 --> 00:02:08.678
to share Reserved Instances,

69
00:02:08.678 --> 00:02:12.090
and finally, the Reserved Instances discount sharing

70
00:02:12.090 --> 00:02:14.960
can be turned off for any accounts in the organization,

71
00:02:14.960 --> 00:02:16.960
including the management accounts,

72
00:02:16.960 --> 00:02:18.910
the main accounts of your organization.

73
00:02:18.910 --> 00:02:19.743
Okay.

74
00:02:19.743 --> 00:02:20.576
That's it for this lecture.

75
00:02:20.576 --> 00:02:21.409
I hope you liked it,

76
00:02:21.409 --> 00:02:22.940
and I will see you in the next lecture.

